**M1 â€” Asserted interfaces are not derived from implementation types**

Every new interface (`CronResult`, `QuotaResetResult`, `TrialExpiryResult`, etc.) is hand-written in the test file and applied via a bare `as TypeName` assertion on the handler result. TypeScript treats `as` as an unconditional override â€” if the underlying Inngest handler ever changes its return shape (renames a field, adds a required key, changes optionality) the assertion will still compile cleanly while tests silently read `undefined`.

Preferred fix: export the return type from the implementation and use it in the test:

```ts
// monthly-report-cron.ts (implementation)
export type CronResult = Awaited<ReturnType<typeof monthlyReportCronFn>>;

// monthly-report-cron.test.ts
import type { CronResult } from './monthly-report-cron';
```

If the implementation uses `(handler as any).fn` making the return type uninferable, a minimum safeguard is a JSDoc comment on each interface stating it was manually audited against the source â€” so future readers know the shape is a confirmed contract, not a guess.

